  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime requires member states to criminalize money laundering.\n\n3. The Palermo Convention provides a framework for international cooperation in fighting organized crime and money laundering.\n\n4. Many countries have implemented their own anti-money laundering (AML) laws, such as:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act in the United States\n- The Proceeds of Crime Act in the United Kingdom\n- The Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorist Financing Act in the European Union\n\n5. International banks and financial institutions are required to implement strict reporting and monitoring procedures to detect and prevent money laundering.\n\nThese laws generally require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Conduct due diligence on high-risk customers\n- Cooperate with law enforcement investigations\n\nWhile specific implementations vary, there is a global consensus on the need to combat money laundering.",
